Those who smoke have a higher risk of losing teeth
If you smoke, you not only harm the lungs, but also the teeth - this is suggested by a Potsdam long-term study.
The good news is that if it waives, the risk quickly decreases.
Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is according to the long-term study of an international team of researchers, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutritional Research (DIfE) in Potsdam.
Compared to non-smokers, smokers were at risk of losing their teeth prematurely, 2.5 to 3.6 times higher.
The scientists had observed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth loss are tooth decay and inflammation of the gums, the DIfE emphasizes.
For this periodontitis, smoking is a risk factor, the authors emphasize.
The association between smoking and tooth loss is therefore due to more frequent gum inflammation in smokers.
It is not clear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of tooth decay.
However, people who quit smoking could reduce their risk within a short period of time, the researchers write in the Journal of Dental Research.
However, it could take more than ten years for the risk to fall back to the level of non-smokers, explained first author Thomas Dietrich from the University of Birmingham in England.
You have to convince people to become non-smokers, explained study leader Heiner Boeing of the DIfE: "Smoking shortens the lifetime."
Not smoking is good for the lungs and vessels and, according to our findings, also leads to good dental health into old age.
In Germany, over 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 are affected by toothlessness, the DIfE said.
Previous research has already indicated that smoking increases the risk of early tooth loss.
The new long-term study backs up the findings.
