Metcash launches down-to-earth campaign to combat Aldi incursion
Metcash is trying to protect the IGA stores from an Aldi march in South Australia and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a down-to-earthness campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia in the run-up to a $700 million Aldi invasion.
While Aldi prepares the opening of two distribution centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food suppliers and building up the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and marketing via social media, as well as through events such as Adelaide show.
IGA dealers and suppliers are jumping on board, with brands such as ice cream maker Simmo from Dunsborough, which distributes samples in IGA stores and shopkeepers who sell discounted tickets for the South Australian Football League to loyal customers.
Metcash is expected to have more details of its defense strategy on 29. September releases when the wholesaler of food, alcohol and appliances conducts its annual investor strategy day.
There is much at stake as South Australia and Western Australia account for nearly 30 per cent of Metcash's IGA store deals and generate higher profit margins than Metcash's IGA network in the Eastern states.
Buyers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland - more than 30 per cent in South Australia and 24 per cent in Western Australia compared to around 14 per cent in the East.
However, analysts like Morgan Stanley believe that twelve months after opening its first markets, Aldi will snatch away about five percent of the food market in these two states and will take away sales from all existing players, but mainly self-employed retailers.
According to a report released this week, analyst Tom Kierath of Morgan Stanley estimated that IGA retailers could lose $360 million in revenue a year and Metcash $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in SA and 30 in WA next year, generating revenue of $500 million and $600 million in each market.
The loss in the food and grocery business and in the volumes on Metcash's high fixed-cost base could cost Metcash around $13 million in profit before interest and tax, Mr Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the Eastern states, mostly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley assumes that Metcash's sales in the food and food business will fall by 3.8 percent in 2016, by 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, and will reduce market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020.
Last week, leading fund manager Hamish Douglass, the founder of the Magellan Financial Group, told at a Melbourne business lunch that Metcash is likely to be within a decade. Metcash will disappear.
Metcash declined to respond publicly to Mr Douglass' comments.
But it is expected that a board member of Metcash made contact with Mr Douglass last week.
IGA's market share has dropped from 18 percent to 14 percent since 2010, and income from Metcash's food and food retailer, which supplies about 1,200 IGA retailers, has fallen 43 percent since 2012, reflecting operational debt reduction while simultaneously putting pressure on sales and margins.
However, the wholesaler is fighting back, investing more than $150 million to match sales prices with Coles and Woolworths on hundreds of products each week, and to improve IGA retailers in improving their stores through fast-growing fresh food and delivering a better selection of private label food.
Metcash's chief executive, Ian Morrice, says the price adjustments and store remediation programs will increase in vigor and hopes the wholesaler will return to profit growth for the first time in four years in 2017.
Thanasi Kokkinakis is backed by Australian Tennis Federation president Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves praise rather than criticism for his behaviour.
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the "collateral damage" in the recent storm around his friend Nick Kyrgios and, according to the president of the Australian Tennis Federation, Steve Healy, deserves praise rather than criticism for his own behaviour.
Kokkinakis, the younger of the talented duo, who is repeatedly referred to as "Special Ks," came into the spotlight through Kyrgios' infamous altercation with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters.
In a fiery qualifying match in Cincinnati soon after, Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee, with Harrison exclaiming: "Wawrinka should have beaten Kyrgios, and I should beat the kid."
While he was last seen smashing a tennis racket after a cramp thwarted a potential U.S. Open victory by Richard Gasquet, Kokkinakis was steadfastly defended by Healy.
The teenager is currently in Glasgow, in competition with Sam Groth for second place in singles behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi-final against Great Britain.
"One thing I'm pretty excited about is the fact that, in my view, Thanasi was drawn into the dispute a little," Healy said.
He broke a racket when he lost in the U.S. Open because of a cramp, but he's not the first player to have broken a racket out of frustration with himself, and I know Thanasi well enough to know he's not proud of it.
But, really, he behaved extremely well in the U.S. Open, even under the pretty provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on, and I think he deserves a lot of recognition.
He has a great team around him, he has a great family around him, and I believe he's been treated a little too harshly.
He's a very mature 19-year-old, he works very hard, and he fits into the team and so on, he's never had a problem with the other players, he's respected in the locker room area, he's training hard, he's in good shape, he's a very stable and mature young guy, and I believe he deserves to be judged by his own merits.
Healy also supported the decision not to take Kyrgios into account in the important preliminary decision, which begins on Friday, and he describes the "common decision" as the right one for everyone, but he assures the man from Canberra to return to the team as a long-term integral part."
"First of all, we wish the team was completely focused on the competition and not on all the controversies all around [Kyrgios]," Healy said.
And I believe that Nick very quickly made the climb, as people like Federer and Murray pointed out. He rises in the eyes of the public, and he has made some bad mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets, but we are trying to support him, we try to make him understand the consequences of his action. Some time outside the spotlight where he can only think about it, I think is appropriate, and it's best for the squad and it's the best for him.
