This is what will happen if the Fed raises interest rates
A rate hike is coming, and the House will falter, yields on bonds will rise, and the economy will slide into a recession.
We know that.
What we don't know is how long this will all last and how long it will last.
In particular, the story offers little guidance on the process for the economy.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first rate hike, and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve's aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, though not always, a factor in how the economy and financial assets are responding.
Therefore, representatives of the US central bank have emphasized so fiercely that investors should not focus on when it begins to raise interest rates, but rather on the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants might find that all the excitement may have been exaggerated because of a rate hike.
"The Fed's first increase since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the era of "cheap money,"" Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a note to clients.
By contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to normal heights, but still at too low levels to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, that does not mean that there will be no impact.
Here's a look based on historical trends on how some areas of the economy might react:
As the market has seen over the last month, anticipating rate hikes can make things volatile for a while.
Once the increase arrives, the influence isn't that dramatic.
"There seems to be a tendency for asset income to be choked off 12 to 24 months after the first increase, which perhaps again reflects the delay in monetary policy," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what's happening after the Fed's rate hikes.
More specifically, the market has mostly been on the upside in the past 35 years - about 14 percent - on the road to interest rate hikes, quite flat in the 250 days after that (average gain of 2.6 percent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the past six past cycles of 14.4 percent, according to a recent analysis that Bob Doll, chief investment strategist at Nuveen Asset Management, published at Barron's.
Deutsche Bank said the impact on the shares tends to occur later in the raise cycle and the yield is beginning to diminish.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rate hikes often encourage them.
In the current case, the Fed is facing some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
What is highly remarkable here is that gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point with a rate hike by the Fed.
According to Deutsche Bank, nominal GDP was below 4.5 percent only twice in the 118 interest rate hikes since 1950.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was at 3.6 percent, few expect this to last and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Interest rate hikes at such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky, raising the question of "whether it's any different this time," Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been preparing for a rate hike by the Fed all year, and all eyes were on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting this week, which ends Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading only indicates a 25 percent probability.
"In our study, all the increase cycles from 1950 to the present have taken place in a super-cycle with increasing momentum in GDP, dwarfing pre-recession heights very quickly after the start of the recovery," the report concluded.
By contrast, this is a clearly slow recovery from what was the worst recession at the observed stage.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
Fixed income was also volatile, as the market anticipates a rate hike, and the pattern is pretty much similar to that on the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than with stocks when they change their strategic course.
For bonds, yields appear to change direction as soon as the first increase/lowering in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond yields are falling immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab's strategists believe the rise in interest rates will cause yields between longer and shorter bonds to move closer together and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-yield bonds often bring better yields in such a climate, though "we're still cautious about expecting higher yields," Kathy Jones, fixed-income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
What's interesting, Jones thinks, markets have already adapted to Fed strategy expectations.
"In addition to the dollar's strength and the fall in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy," she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit margins have widened and volatility has risen - all features of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
On the whole, companies that handle the greater part of their business in the U.S. will benefit as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational companies with high debt will be worse off as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market and also the financing of their debts.
"History shows that "quality" stocks tend to respond exceedingly positively three months after an initial rate hike," Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for the clients.
Companies with a strong balance sheet have averaged 5 percentage points on average for companies with a weak balance sheet after each of the interest rate hikes in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high returns on capital and low volatility in their shares also exceeded their low-quality counterparts by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points).
Debt is becoming a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of pure stock games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see gains through higher yields, even if experts disagree on how quickly that will happen.
