At their most anticipated meeting in the year, Federal Reserve strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduras-Mahogany table to decide whether it's time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Threatening above them at one end of the ornate, two-storey boardroom is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are supposed to put the economic interests of the nation before all other things.
The central bank has a twofold order from Congress: maximizing U.S. employment and keeping prices stable here.
But since the great recession, the Fed leaders have acknowledged that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And that third mandate could be the X factor in a decision that is too tight to predict. It will be announced on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to be weaned off by the unprecedented incentive from the near-to-zero short-term interest rate since late 2008.
Although most of the economy's data shows it's growing solidly, recent turmoil in global financial markets could make the already cautious Fed representatives anxious to step up that volatility by raising the rate on federal bonds - and even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be first and foremost the most important thing they are observing," Lindsey M said. Piegza, chief economist at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think if they were looking for a pretext not to raise the interest rate, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough justification to continue to wait," she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, what in itself unsettles the financial market.
About half of economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg have predicted a rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to wait, with a key indicator that only shows a 30% chance of an increase.
This suggests a drop in the stock market in case the Fed raises the rate, unless the strategists mitigate the blow by promising that another increase is far away.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The action was sparked by expectations that Fed policy will maintain the rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed were to lift the sentences at this point," he said.
If she does, "she would have to go very far in her statement to calm financial markets so that they don't panic."
Other experts argued that a rate hike would calm financial markets because it would eliminate uncertainty about when the Fed will trade.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of recovery in the U.S.
Yellen had said in the spring and early summer that she expected an increase in the rate this year despite the complaints from liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, improvement in the labor market this year has been solid.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed considers full employment.
Wage increases have shown signs of recovery.
And although inflation was constantly below the central bank's annual target of 2%, the Fed representatives said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can handle higher interest rates and needs them because of the tension in the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world shrugged late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial average fell more than 16% below its peak in May, when investors feared that a slowdown in the Chinese economy would throttle global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, with the Dow now nearly 10% below the May high.
For the Fed representatives, the market turmoil affects the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
"If events in the financial markets and the news of the weakness of the Chinese economy had not occurred in the last few weeks, they would be pulling the reins in this session," Stephen D said. Oliner, Senior Research Fellow at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former employee of the U.S. Federal Reserve.
Now he predicts she will wait at least a month to better handle the impact.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and there is almost no reliable data describing developments in China," Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed's primary concerns, so it should not be technically involved in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the world.
The central bank's influence has been enormous in recent years.
The mere hint of the then-head Ben S. Bernanke in 2013, that the Fed could "constrict" its monetary expansion, sparked confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed representatives may be expected to not only monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of the global strategy for wealth management at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA., noted this month that "the Fed has a history of overreactions to financial market movements that are apparently not linked to economic fundamentals."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, which advocates for a rate hike, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to cut its key interest rate by 0.75 percentage points in three sessions "despite limited discernible impact on U.S. growth," Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed representatives reversed those cuts.
The Fed should put aspects of financial stability first only during a serious crisis such as the 2008 market collapse, Adam S said. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate fixing committee.
The recent turmoil is not coming close to that level, he said.
"She certainly doesn't want to get into the situation where she's afraid of a rate hike because the markets are getting upset," said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains the double mandate and doesn't mention financial stability, and until that is changed, I don't think it should rush ahead of time.
