Robotic cars: Government wants pioneering role for Germany
According to the will of the German government, Germany should be a technological pioneer in the transformation of the car.
The Federal Cabinet decided on Wednesday a strategy paper from the House of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which provides for investment in the expansion of digital infrastructure, among other things.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the sidelines of the car show IAA of a "new mobility age."
Automated and connected driving will increase road safety and cause less congestion, Dobrindt said.
He also wants to discuss the issue with his counterparts from the G7 countries, who will also meet with industry representatives at the IAA.
The strategy paper of the Ministry of Transport emphasizes, among other things, the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a rapid switch to digital radio.
A test track is currently being built on Autobahn 9 in Bavaria to test new technology.
In order to ensure that the driver "is not burdened with additional liability risks", the Federal Government wants to "review the legal framework and, where necessary, adapt it to the new developments".
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to increase the permissible maximum speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometers per hour.
The Federal Government also wants to campaign for an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for the people as drivers.
When driving automatically, the car increasingly takes over the lead, the driver becomes more and more a passenger.
The technology is primarily based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study presented by the Ministry of Economic Affairs, highly automated driving on motorways will be technically possible by 2020.
Nevertheless, driverless vehicles on public roads are "only expected far after 2020."
The authors of the study estimate the added value in the field of driver assistance systems and the highly automated driving functions in Germany at around 8.4 billion euros for 2025.
"The digital networking of the car can lead to more safety and efficiency in road traffic," said SPD transport politician Sören Bartol.
However, the question of liability in the event of accidents and the safety of the personal data of the drivers must be clearly clarified.
However, the Germans still see self-driving cars skeptically - much more than French or Americans.
A survey presented on Wednesday at the AA by the Forsa Institute on behalf of the testing organization Dekra concludes that only eight percent of Germans believe that autonomously driving cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32 percent expect it only in 20 years, 31 percent do not believe in it at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomously driving cars by 2025, and 33 percent in the United States.
In any case, motorists in Germany are not yet ready to rely completely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to surrender control throughout the journey on all roads.
On the highway, 15 percent could imagine this in the flowing traffic, 45 percent in traffic jams.
Well one in four would not leave the car the control under any circumstances.
