EU wants to double mercury limit in predatory fish
The European Commission wants to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fish, thus expecting consumers to have a significantly higher dose of the nerve agent.
The consumer organization Foodwatch, which has a corresponding working paper of the EU, sharply criticized the plans: "Risks and side effects of failed industrial and environmental policy are passed on with full force to pregnant women and toddlers," explained Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limits of the nerve agent for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as shark or swordfish, are to be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic policy reasons".
However, large predators are already so heavily contaminated with mercury that about 50 percent of the catches may not be sold on the basis of the still applicable limit values.
After doubling the limit values, only 14.5 percent would be unsaleable.
In return for this easing, the EU wants to tighten the limits on other fish from the current 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram, according to Foodwatch.
However, Foodwatch described this as a "trick" because smaller fried fish, such as carp, are usually so low-loaded that they already comply with the planned maximum values today.
The reduction in small fish is therefore "a perfidious distraction maneuver that helps the economy alone," Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a highly toxic heavy metal for humans, which accumulates strongly across the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The German government therefore warns that "already small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in the case of unborn babies."
However, the Federal Ministry for the Environment declares on its homepage with regard to the applicable maximum values that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury is mainly released into the environment through coal combustion.
According to a written information from the Federal Environment Ministry, the German coal-fired power plants emit more than six tons of mercury a year, two-thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany, two thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany.
The concentration of mercury in fish, for example in the Elbe, Rhine and Danube, was "permanently and extensively exceeded," had quoted the "Mirror" in March from the paper.
Last year, Europe-wide warnings of mercury in fish were already among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU warning system RASFF.
